1. Core Principle for Large Data Visualization

Large interactive plots should use:

Large Dataset
     ↓
Fast storage engine
     ↓
Query subset / aggregation
     ↓
Downsample data
     ↓
Render interactive plot

Plotting 1 million points directly in a browser is slow, but 5–20k points is smooth.

2. Fast Data Handling in R
Best option: Columnar data engines

Use:

Apache Arrow

DuckDB

These are much faster than loading full CSV files into R memory.

Why they are fast

column-based reading

lazy queries

memory mapping

vectorized computation

Example with DuckDB
library(DBI)
library(duckdb)

con <- dbConnect(duckdb())

dbExecute(con, "CREATE TABLE data AS SELECT * FROM read_csv_auto('bigdata.csv')")

subset <- dbGetQuery(con,"
SELECT time, power
FROM data
WHERE time BETWEEN 100 AND 200
")

DuckDB can query GB datasets instantly.

Example with Arrow
library(arrow)

dataset <- open_dataset("data_folder")

subset <- dataset %>%
  filter(time > 100) %>%
  select(time, power) %>%
  collect()

Arrow only reads the required columns.

3. Use Data Downsampling

Even if you have 1M points, show only 5k–10k points.

Best method:

Largest Triangle Three Buckets (LTTB)

Used by many time-series systems.

Benefits:

preserves shape

extremely fast

ideal for signals

Libraries:

rLTTB

JS libraries

Example:

library(LTTB)

downsampled <- lttb(data, n_out = 5000)
4. Fast Interactive Plotting

The fastest interactive plotting libraries for large datasets are:

In R

plotly

echarts4r

highcharter

Best for large datasets

ECharts handles millions of points smoothly.

Example:

library(echarts4r)

df |> 
 e_charts(time) |>
 e_line(power) |>
 e_datazoom()

dataZoom enables dynamic zooming.

5. Even Faster: WebGL Rendering

For huge datasets use WebGL plotting.

Libraries:

deck.gl

Three.js

Plotly.js (WebGL mode)

Example Plotly WebGL:

plot_ly(
  data=df,
  x=~time,
  y=~power,
  type='scattergl',
  mode='lines'
)

scattergl uses GPU acceleration.

